47:12.763 --> 47:17.435 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Composer and musician Rob
Kapilow is back
to tell us why the music has
withstood the

47:17.468 --> 47:19.070 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
test of time.

47:19.103 --> 47:20.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown sat down with
Kapilow recently.

47:20.671 --> 47:22.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Ron Kapilow,
welcome back.

47:22.206 --> 47:23.974 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW, Composer: It's
great to be here.

47:24.008 --> 47:27.545 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, "West Side
Story," one
of the most famous musicals in
history, but

47:27.578 --> 47:30.414 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not quite what it was intended
to be, I guess.

47:30.448 --> 47:32.283 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: I think that's
true.

47:32.316 --> 47:36.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, Leonard Bernstein had
already written
two his musicals, "On the Town"
and "Wonderful

47:36.153 --> 47:40.658 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Town," and those shows are
filled with Bernstein's
love, facility, and affection
for the popular

47:40.691 --> 47:41.759 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
music of the day.

47:41.792 --> 47:44.261 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But they're lighthearted
musicals, fundamentally.

47:44.295 --> 47:49.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And now he wanted to do
something serious,
and he got together an
incredibly serious

47:49.166 --> 47:50.301 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
crew of guys.

47:50.334 --> 47:52.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, we had Jerome Robbins,
who did serious
ballets.

47:52.837 --> 47:55.473 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We had Arthur Laurents, who
wrote serious
plays.

47:55.506 --> 47:59.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We had Leonard Bernstein, and
they wanted
to do something serious.

47:59.210 --> 48:00.911 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That was the amazing thing about
Bernstein.

48:00.945 --> 48:03.681 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He could actually do both, and
he crossed
over.

48:03.714 --> 48:08.385 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this whole piece is really
about, in a
way, the conflict between those
two worlds,

48:08.419 --> 48:10.054 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
between the serious world.

48:10.087 --> 48:14.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is going to be, he called a
tragic musical
comedy, if that's not an
oxymoron.

48:14.825 --> 48:17.728 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Tragedies get
turned into operas
all the time.

48:17.762 --> 48:18.829 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: All the time.

48:18.863 --> 48:20.498 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
In fact, tragedy is the
lifeblood of opera.

48:20.531 --> 48:22.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not really an opera unless
somebody dies
at the end.

48:23.000 --> 48:25.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But people don't usually die at
the end in
a Broadway musical.

48:25.903 --> 48:30.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And this one had a body count of
three, with
two of them dead at the first
act curtain.

48:30.708 --> 48:35.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, that is not the stuff of
a Broadway
musical, not to mention a
classic Shakespeare

48:35.613 --> 48:37.381 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
play, "Romeo and Juliet," as the
background.

48:37.414 --> 48:41.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Most people, of
course, know
"West Side Story" from the film,
the musical

48:42.019 --> 48:42.987 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
version.

48:43.020 --> 48:43.988 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROB KAPILOW: True.

48:44.021 --> 48:45.189 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
True.

48:45.222 --> 48:45.990 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So use the song
"Maria," a
famous song.

48:46.023 --> 48:47.024 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Famous song.

48:47.057 --> 48:48.759 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Show us what
turned out there.

48:48.793 --> 48:50.694 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Well, there's a
great moment
in the middle of "Maria," which
shows this

48:50.728 --> 48:53.764 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
battle intention between opera
and Broadway.

48:53.798 --> 48:59.103 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The orchestra is playing the
music of the
opening as if it's become
somehow Tony's subconscious

48:59.136 --> 49:00.104 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mind.

49:00.137 --> 49:01.772 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTOR (singing): Maria.

49:01.806 --> 49:12.016 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have just kissed a girl named
Maria, and
suddenly I found how wonderful a
song can

49:12.049 --> 49:13.384 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
be.

49:13.417 --> 49:20.558 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Beautiful chord,
and all the
warmth.

49:20.591 --> 49:27.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, that's what the orchestra
is doing, but,
above it, in the film, Tony, as
if rhapsodizing

49:27.164 --> 49:38.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about this Maria, the sound and
the single
word gets higher and higher in
pitch, until

49:38.843 --> 49:47.518 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
finally climaxes up here, Maria,
and then
in the film, sings this.

49:47.551 --> 49:50.721 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTOR (singing): Maria.

49:50.754 --> 49:51.789 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Maria.

49:51.822 --> 49:52.857 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Maria.

49:52.890 --> 49:53.924 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Maria.

49:53.958 --> 49:55.292 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Maria.

49:55.326 --> 50:01.632 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: Now, that's kind of
operatic,
but it's lower in pitch.

50:01.665 --> 50:03.601 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: We're not holding
you to just
sing it again.

50:03.634 --> 50:04.602 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: But -- exactly.

50:04.635 --> 50:06.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No one's vocal chords are
straining.

50:06.203 --> 50:08.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No one's blood vessels are
bursting.

50:08.539 --> 50:12.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's doable eight times a week,
and for the
public, it was perfectly
successful.

50:12.476 --> 50:16.380 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Right, but that's
not the opera
version that Bernstein wanted.

50:16.413 --> 50:18.048 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: That's not what he
wanted.

50:18.082 --> 50:20.918 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He comes from the world of being
one of the
great opera conductors.

50:20.951 --> 50:25.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, was there ever a more
over-the-top,
larger-than-life, operatic
personality than

50:25.623 --> 50:27.358 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Bernstein?

50:27.391 --> 50:40.537 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, he writes a version that
goes higher,
and higher, and higher, and
finally climaxes

50:40.571 --> 50:45.209 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on a high B-flat held for 10
beats.

50:45.242 --> 50:47.811 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTOR (singing): Maria!

50:47.845 --> 50:53.951 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: This is something
right out of
"La Bohem" or "La Traviata."

50:53.984 --> 50:56.720 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You literally see the vocal
chords bursting.

50:56.754 --> 51:00.691 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, eventually, they had to get
rid of it,
and Bernstein was so depressed
because he

51:00.724 --> 51:04.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
