and he actually
went back later and recorded it
with opera

51:27.051 --> 51:29.420 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
singers, with the incredibly
high B-flat.

51:29.453 --> 51:35.926 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Your argument is
that somehow
in the tension between this
opera and musical,

51:35.960 --> 51:38.862 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
high and low, I guess, something
great happened.

51:38.896 --> 51:40.698 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ROB KAPILOW: Yes.

51:40.731 --> 51:43.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the great things about
Bernstein was
that he moved so effortlessly
between the

51:43.067 --> 51:48.372 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
worlds of serious music and
popular music,
and he spoke both languages
absolutely as

51:48.405 --> 51:50.207 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
if they were vernacular.

51:50.240 --> 51:54.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what's interesting is the
tension between
what he brought to the world of
the Broadway

51:54.211 --> 52:00.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
musical was the entire world of
serious classical
music, yet he also spoke it in a
natural way

52:00.985 --> 52:03.053 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that other classical composers
didn't.

52:03.087 --> 52:06.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And the end of this piece is a
perfect example.

52:06.390 --> 52:13.564 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ACTOR (singing): The most
beautiful song I
ever heard.

52:13.597 --> 52:19.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: It ends with opera,
but not the
high opera that we think of
opera, but the

52:19.336 --> 52:26.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
intimate world of opera, a
floated voice,
a falsetto voice, not the first
Maria, Maria,

52:26.477 --> 52:31.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not the second one, Maria, but a
final one
that resolves Maria for the
first time in

52:31.915 --> 52:36.553 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the piece, Maria.

52:36.587 --> 52:43.127 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ACTOR (singing): Maria.

52:43.160 --> 52:51.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROB KAPILOW: And while a tenor,
only an operatic
tenor can do it well, floats
this high note,

52:52.002 --> 53:00.611 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the orchestra goes, and we end
the perfect
merging of Broadway musical and
the world

53:00.644 --> 53:01.612 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of opera.

53:01.645 --> 53:03.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: "West Side
Story."

